<h2>
  <a name="gruppe"></a>
  Which groups of individuals will I find in the interview collection?
</h2>
<p>
  <span lang="EN-US">The archive “Forced Labor 1939-1945” contains interviews with individuals who were victims of National Socialism in different ways during the Second World War. German victims after the war (e.g. German prisoners of war in the Soviet Union, German forced laborers in Poland or Czechoslovakia) are not represented in the archive. Those interviewed were predominantly individuals who were compelled to perform forced labor in one form or another. In order to ensure precise research, the individual groups of forced laborers have been categorized as precisely as possible: OST-Arbeiter (Eastern workers) or Service du Travail obligatoire; in other cases (particularly, in the case of the Polish forced laborers and individuals who had to perform forced labor in their home countries) the category “Forced Laborers” is used. Along with the specific designation “Italian Military Internee” (IMI), the more general term “Prisoner of War” is also found.</span>
</p>
<p>
  <span lang="EN-US">Victims of racist persecution (Jews as well as Sinti and Roma) and those who were persecuted for political and religious reasons (<span>Jehovah's Witnesses or Orthodox Serbs in Croatia) are each represented as a separate group. Not all of them were interned in concentration camps. For this reason, there is also a separate category for concentration camp prisoners, especially because this group of people defines itself less in terms of the forced labor they performed, but rather through their persecution and internment as those who are “different”.</span><br/>Most people went through various stages of persecution: from captivity to civilian forced labor or from forced labor to political persecution and concentration camp internment. Germanized children represent a special case. The category “Miscellaneous” includes those who cannot be clearly assigned to a category based on the information available.</span>
</p>
