<h2>
  <a name="unterbringung"></a>
  What does “Internment Conditions” mean?
</h2>
<p>
  <span lang="EN-US">Along with the areas of deployment and working conditions, the site and conditions of internment determined the forced laborers’ living conditions and chances of survival. The category “Internment Conditions” enables a quick search of the witnesses interviewed according to the various conditions:</span>
</p>
<p>
  <span lang="EN-US">Camps (including prisoner of war camps) are distinguished from concentration camps as well as Arbeitserziehungslager (work education camps), which were a specific form of punitive treatment against civilian foreign workers. People were also interned in prisons. For so-called private accommodation, the following are distinguished from each other: internment conditions “At the Labor Site” (in some cases this also includes non-private accommodation when this designation applies) and “At Home” (for laborers who were not deported) as well as “Private Accommodation” (for insofar privileged foreign laborers for whom collective accommodation was not assigned). The establishment of ghettos for Jews represents a special case and for this reason the category “Ghettos” has also been incorporated. The category “Miscellaneous” encompasses those conditions of internment that cannot be clearly assigned to a category. In some cases the corresponding information is not available.</span>
</p>
