<h2>
  <a name="surschik"></a>
  What is Surzhyk?
</h2>
<p>
  The language situation in Ukraine was characterized for centuries by a “side
  by side” coexistence of Ukrainian and
  Russian. Since 1991, Ukrainian has become the official language of Ukraine.
  Through a history of long and intensive
  contact with the Russian language and as a result of gradual Russification
  during the Soviet Era, a language variety
  emerged among the people: Surzhyk (from the Ukrainian, суржик = “low-quality
  flour made from mixed grains”). The term
  is a colloquial collective label for a mixed dialect arising from Ukrainian
  and Russian. In their
  efforts to speak Russian, the frequently inadequately educated rural
  population produced a language variety adapted
  from the Ukrainian but whose vocabulary consisted essentially of Russian
  words. Hence, Russian emerges predominantly
  in the lexicon and Ukrainian in the grammar. This Ukrainian-Russian mix of
  languages is spoken in many parts of
  Ukraine and in some western regions of Russia. According to statistics
  published by the Kiev International Sociology
  Institute in 2003, surzhyk is spoken by around one fifth of the population,
  e.g. 21.7%, east of
  Central Ukraine. Central Ukraine follows with 14.6%, followed by the South
  with 12.4%, the East with 9.6% and the West
  with 2.5%, where the Ukrainian language has traditionally been very strong. A
  similar language phenomenon can be
  observed in Belarus: Trasianka or <strong>trasyanka</strong> (Belarusian:
  трасянка) is a widely spread mix of
  languages in Belarus consisting of Belarusian and Russian.
  <strong>Surzhyk</strong> and <strong>trasianka</strong>
  have been investigated very little in descriptive linguistics until now.
</p>
